  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reflections Written During Illness
  author: Jeong Hee-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sun descends beyond the mountain pass, miasmic fog spreads thick.
    A mournful flute's cry stirs the frontier garrison.
    The general unfolds his emerald tent for a luminous feast,
    While I, a wanderer, face the western wind by my dim lamp.

    Poetic lines are born, strange to say, from sorrow's depth.
    A traveler's yearning swells most keenly in sickness.
    In daylight, demons flock to mock and keep me company—
    In this empty study, I sit alone, startled by my own silence.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The flute (角) evokes the traditional military instrument of the frontier, lending both historical resonance and melancholic atmosphere.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the general's festive gathering and the speaker's solitary vigil reflects the poet's sense of exclusion and alienation.
  - key: ''
    value: 魑魅 (demons/goblins) may be read both literally and as a metaphor for the disturbing thoughts and anxieties that plague the sickbed.
